post_text:
If you are not learning virtually, TOMORROW is your first on-campus day of learning for only the following grades: 12th grade, 6th grade, 5th grade, Kindergarten. If you are a BravesID distance learner, you do not report to campus. If you are an on-campus learner in any grade besides 12th grade, 6th grade, 5th grade, or Kindergarten, you will report to campus later this week.

School Times
Elementary
Doors Open at 7 AM
School Starts at 7:30 AM
Dismissal at 3:20 PM

Middle School
Doors Open 7:45 AM
1st Period Starts at 8:20 AM
Dismissal 4:10 PM

High School
Doors Open 7:45 AM
1st Period Starts at 8:20 AM
Dismissal 4:10 PM

Starting Monday, June 29th, access to track and football field will remain open for the community with the following restrictions:

Home side bleachers will remain closed

All areas around and outside the track will remain closed

The only entrance will be the south gate

post_text:
On Monday, June 15, 2020, new CHS Head Football Coach Dustin Blann was officially introduced to the CISD Board of Trustees. A graduate of Baylor University, Coach Blann earned his Masters in Education Administration from Lamar University. He comes to the Brave Nation with 19 years of experience as a teacher-coach. Most recently, he served as the Offensive Coordinator at 5A Terrell High School. He has held the same position with 6A Naaman Forest High School, 4A Baytown Lee High School, and 4A Polytechnic High School.

Coach Blann shared with the Board, “I’m humbled and grateful for the opportunity to serve as the Head Football Coach of Community High School. I look forward to molding our Braves into young men of strong character who will be future leaders.”

post_text:
We are thankful for the passionate service of Ms. Donna Dickerson as she retires from CISD after 23 years of service in the Brave Nation. Ms. Dickersoon began her career in education teaching 5th Grade Science at Community Middle School in 1997. She also taught 2nd, 3rd, and 4th grade Math, Reading, Science, and Social Studies at McClendon. She served as the K-5 Math Interventionist for both NeSmith and McClendon Elementary. Ms. Dickerson is wrapping up her career as the Instructional Coach for Edge Middle School.

We asked Ms. Dickerson what would be her advice to a new teacher: “My best advice to a brand new teacher is to be open to feedback and willing to try new things. However, most importantly surround yourself with open, positive people who have a growth mindset. If they can challenge you to try new things then you can only be successful.”

Congratulations on your retirement Ms. Dickerson!

post_text:
As we approach the end of our school year and conclusion of #BravesID it is time to return district-issued technology devices.

Technology return will be held May 26th - 29th at Edge MS North parking lot (parent pickup parking lot near band hall)

drop off dates/times:

Tuesday, May 26th, from 9 AM-12 PM, Last names A-H

Wednesday, May 27th, from 9 AM-12 PM, Last names I-Q

Thursday, May 28th, from 9 AM-12 PM, Last names R-Z

Friday, May 29th, 3 PM-6 PM, anyone that couldn't make it on their designated day

Students completing summer school with Community ISD or Collin College will keep their devices and have a later turn-in date.

Please note: CISD Technology will be charging for any visible damage and discuss the damage with the parents if needed. We will only charge the cost of the parts and these are the prices:

Screen: $20
Touch Screen: $80
Keyboard: $40
Base/Lid: $20
Charger: $20
Hotspot: $50
Destroyed/Lost Device: $150

If you have questions, please email: techhelp@communityisd.org

post_text:
Let's celebrate the SUPERIOR performances this year by our Community Braves Band!!! Our award-winning band, winter guard, and indoor percussion teams brought home recognition from EIGHT contests during an abbreviated contest season! Additionally, 36 of our Braves received superior ratings for their solo or ensemble performances, 27 student-musicians advanced to State, 11 members of the CHS Band were named to the TMEA Regional Band, and 2 were named to the TMEA Area Band.

We are so proud of our Mighty Braves Band!
Read more: https://tinyurl.com/Superior-CHS-Band2020

🌱🌼💙
shared_text:
Ashley Elizabeth Crowe is at McClendon Elementary.
April 25 at 11:55 AM · Instagram ·

I planted my #bravesbloom Forget Me Not seeds around 3 weeks ago, and their first true leaves have emerged. They stopped me in my tracks and I paused to say a prayer of thanks that we still have this opportunity to learn and #growtogether from a distance. I love teaching my 5th grade Braves, our online lessons, LIVE hangouts, and more. Although being separated by distance is not ideal we have adapted and are making the best of this! Who else’s Braves Bloom seeds are thriving and growing? I would love to see! 💙 💛 #mesblessed #bravesid Community Independent School District

post_text:
It's time for another Online Roll Call! We want to know what our Braves are doing for fun when they aren't learning! Show us how your Braves pass the time with safe hobbies at home...maybe it's fishing, gaming, puzzles, working out, taking care of animals, gardening, or building things.

Take a picture of your Brave doing the thing they love to do the most when they aren't learning and post it in the comments below.

You have until 3 PM on Monday, April 27 to submit your entry. We will select a winner for the most interesting hobby, the best photo, AND we will randomly select up to FIVE entries for a golden hoodie!!! (If you are a previous Golden Hoodie winner, you may enter but are not eligible to win again.)

By submitting your photo you grant CISD permission to publish the photo. Judges will select winners to be announced on Tuesday, April 28. Golden Hoodie prizes will be mailed or delivered to your porch shortly after.

post_text: Who else has planted your #BravesBloom seeds? Let us see where your blooms will grow by sharing a photo with the hashtag #BravesBloom. If you haven't already picked up your seed packets, they are available for FREE at four of our local businesses who are deemed essential or take-out. All you have to do is ask for the Community ISD seed packets at the counter or window. Please take one for each Brave in your family. Thank you to CWC Creations, Crossroads (Nevada), Josephine Market, and MLK Mart (Shell Station) in Lavon for helping us safely share the seed packets. Let's grow together!

post_text: #BravesID Update: On Friday, April 17, 2020, Governor Abbott issued an updated executive order regarding the status of COVID-19 related restrictions and closures in Texas. As part of this order, all school buildings in the state will be closed for the remainder of the school year, however, learning will continue. Read more in this very important message from Dr. Nivens:
shared_text:
SMORE.COM
Important Message from Dr. Nivens
text:
#BravesID Update: On Friday, April 17, 2020, Governor Abbott issued an updated executive order regarding the status of COVID-19 related restrictions and closures in Texas. As part of this order, all school buildings in the state will be closed for the remainder of the school year, however, learning will continue. Read more in this very important message from Dr. Nivens:

post_text:
Here is a quick history lesson courtesy of the winners for our #BravesIDHistory online roll call!

George Washington had to quit school when he was 11 years old because his father died and his mother needed him to help her with the farm. Betsy Ross claimed to have done tailoring for George Washington. Alexander Graham Bell co-founded the American Telephone and Telegraph Company (AT&T), and Sacagawea's birthday is unknown reported to be in two different birth years, 1786 and 1787.

Thank you to these Brave historians for sharing! If George Washington, Betsy Ross, Alexander Graham Bell or Sacagawea belongs to you, please email info@communityisd.org to claim their golden hoodie!

McClendon Elementary
April 3 at 4:40 PM ·

Please join me in congratulating Mrs. Porter as our McClendon Teacher of the Year and Mrs. McMaster as our Support Staff of the Year.

Mrs. Porter was described by her colleagues as: "Passionate- shows passion by always going above and beyond in creating engaging lessons for her students" and "Porter is humble and shares her success with others / continues to work for the success of all students"

Mrs. McMaster was described by her colleagues as: "She is a breath of fresh air for our library rotation. She has filled a void that has been there for many years. The kids love her and her activities. " and "She's passionate about reading. She's wise in her lesson planning, offering students a wide variety of interesting lessons and topics during library classes. She's humble in her willingness to help"

We are so lucky to have amazing staff members at MES. Congratulations!

Let's celebrate the end of our second week of #BravesID on Friday, April 3, with another Online Roll Call!! Our theme this week is: Braves, where ART thou? Let us see your artistic side! Create a masterpiece and post your picture in the comments below.

Here are some tips and ideas:

Have some sidewalk chalk? Decorate your driveway or sidewalk.

Draw or paint a picture of your family and hang it in your front window.

Create a sculpture or collage with things around your house.

You have until the end of the roll call day (Friday, April 3) to submit your entry. Only one entry per Brave per online roll call. By submitting your photo you grant CISD permission to publish the photo.

Judges will select a winner for most creative, most Brave Nation spirit, and most impressive. Winners will be announced on Monday, April 6. Golden Hoodie prizes will be mailed or delivered shortly after.

Ready, Go!

👱‍♂️👱‍♀️Parents, helping your kids with distance learning while still going to work, or working from home, and managing life during a pandemic is HARD.

👧👨‍🎓Students, not being able to see your friends or do all the things really stinks.

🧑‍💻👩‍🏫Teachers, being apart from kids and delivering remote instruction is a challenge everyday.

💙🏹Brave Nation, it’s understandable if you are feeling sad, scared, disappointed, or overwhelmed.

🤔 Did you know? Experts say hugging releases oxytocin which reduces stress and can improve immune function. So, we are sending you a virtual hug from Lacone Jo to say we love you. We miss you. We believe in you. Hang in there. We will get through this together!

➡️Share this post with someone who needs a virtual hug.

🖥 visit communityISD.org/COVID-19 for healthy activities and tips for managing stress.

post_text: #HealthyBraves
shared_text:
HHS.TEXAS.GOV
HHS Launches Statewide COVID-19 Mental Health Support Line | Texas Health and Human Services

Josephine Police Department
April 1 at 2:06 PM ·

HHSC Statewide COVID-19 Mental Health Support Line:

The Texas Health and Human Services Commission (HHSC) has launched a statewide mental health support line to help Texans experiencing anxiety, stress, or other emotional challenges due to the COVID-19 pandemic. This resource offers support for all Texans and can be reached any time day or night at 833-986-1919.

The line is operated by the Harris Center for Mental Health and IDD, and offers trauma-informed support and psychological first aid to those experiencing mental health symptoms related to COVID-19. Counseling services are confidential and free of charge.

More information on mental health resources and your local metal health authority can be found on HHSC's website.

https://hhs.texas.gov/about-hhs/communications-events/news/2020/03/hhs-launches-statewide-covid-19-mental-health-support-line

Let's celebrate the end of our second week of #BravesID on Friday, April 3, with another Online Roll Call!! Our theme this week is: Braves, where ART thou? Let us see your artistic side! Create a masterpiece and post your picture in the comments below.

Here are some tips and ideas:

Have some sidewalk chalk? Decorate your driveway or sidewalk.

Draw or paint a picture of your family and hang it in your front window.

Create a sculpture or collage with things around your house.

You have until the end of the roll call day (Friday, April 3) to submit your entry. Only one entry per Brave per online roll call. By submitting your photo you grant CISD permission to publish the photo.

Judges will select a winner for most creative, most Brave Nation spirit, and most impressive. Winners will be announced on Monday, April 6. Golden Hoodie prizes will be mailed or delivered shortly after.

Ready, Go!

post_text:
On Tuesday, March 31, Governor Abbott issued an executive order extending the closure of all school buildings. This means that Monday, May 4th is currently the earliest date to reopen schools in Texas. We are keeping the hope and a positive mindset that we will defeat COVID-19 and be able to return to our buildings to see our Braves by this date. During this time Community ISD will continue to provide instruction through BravesID distance learning, as well as deliver meals through our regular bus routes.

Please continue to follow all local and state stay-at-home directives and CDC recommendations for social distancing to protect yourself and your Braves from illness.

For the latest updates and information on COVID-19 go to communityisd.org/COVID-19 and for resources to support BravesID distance learning, visit communityisd.org/BravesID

Let’s stay safe, stay home and stay healthy in the Brave Nation!

March 20 at 5:33 PM ·

It's finally here, our first day of school (from a distance!) Monday, March 23!!! We want to check in with our Braves and stay connected while we are apart. So, once a week we will have online roll call.....with prizes!!

Here's how this will work. When we post an online roll call, you have until the end of the roll call day to submit your entry. You must follow the directions and use the specific hashtag. Only one entry per Brave per online roll call. Judges will select a winner (or winners) to be announced the following day. Prizes will be delivered or mailed soon after.

Ok, Brave Nation, Online Roll Call for Monday, March 23, 2020:

1. Take a selfie (or a picture of your Brave) in the new learning space
2. Post a single photo in the comments of this post with the hashtag #1stDayBravesID (or email it to info@communityisd.org)
3. We will select a winner for the most creative space AND the most spirited Brave

Ready, Go!!!

post_text:
Dear Brave parents, grandparents, guardians,

We know you may be feeling overwhelmed with all that is going on in the world and now your Braves are home and #BravesID learning from home starts on Monday......whew! Please know that we are here to help. If you don't know where to start with Google Classroom, take a look at this guide created just for you:

https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1K66iHUzNKpceGIqtEogcOBUp2wAMg1me1tZGWDk7OEg/present?slide=id.g4f60ec15fb_1_0

BravesID Tip: All students have been enrolled in Google Classroom. The login is their CISD student email address (first three letters of first name + first three letters of last name + the two-digit birth month + cisdbraves.org) example: Melissa Jones, born in May = meljon05@cisdbraves.org. The password is the student ID#.

For tech help/questions: techhelp@communityisd.org
For other help/questions: info@communityisd.org

post_text:
Communication Alert: On Tuesday, March 17 and Wednesday, March 18, our teachers will be calling to check on each of our Braves. We need some critical information from our families as we prepare for a shift to instructional delivery from a distance. Please be on the look out for calls coming from our campus numbers, or perhaps an unknown or private number as some of our staff are using their personal phones. If you have multiple students, you should receive one call for each of them. Please be patient with us as we don't want to miss making contact with any of our students.

Additional information about school operations and instructional delivery will be shared later this week. In the meantime, thank you for your patience and support as we are working hard to adjust our school plans. We know this is a difficult time for our families who are also also having to adjust to this unforeseen situation. Remember, we are #BraveStrong and we will get through this as one #CommUNITY.

post_text:
During this challenging and unprecedented time, taking care of our students remains our greatest responsibility. Beginning Wednesday, March 18, CISD Child Nutrition and our Transportation team will deliver free breakfast from 8 - 9 AM and free lunch between 11:30 AM - 12:30 PM via our regular bus stops. Meals are free for any student under 18 but the student must be present to accept the meal. (Use this link to find your meal drop-off times: http://www.infofinderi.com/ifi/?cid=CI38IS5PI6A)

Our district is 89 square miles and many of our students are at home with no transportation to bring them to a remote campus feeding location. In order to ensure that our Braves have access to food, we decided to deliver meals to the students via our regular bus routes. Parents and community members, please help us remind students to maintain a distance from each other at the bus stop and not stand in groups. If a parent or student is ill, or if your family has been asked to self-quarantine, please do not attend one of the bus stop drop-off locations.

CISD Parents/Guardians: during the coming days we will be sending very important updates and information via our Blackboard messaging system. Earlier today we sent an email to all parents who have not previously logged in to Blackboard. If you have not already, please download the CISD mobile app with the links provided in the email and sign in with the username and password provided. If you did not receive an email please check your spam. If you still don’t see the Blackboard email and you do not already have a Blackboard account and the CISD mobile app, please email info@communityisd.org with your name and the names/grades of your Braves.

Once you log in, if you do not see one of your children listed, please email info@communityisd.org.

We will also be posting all updates and information on our dedicated webpage for COVID-19 resources and news: communityisd.org/COVID-19

Community ISD Athletic Department
March 6 at 4:35 PM ·

Congratulations to our Lady Braves for getting 3rd place as a team at the Regional Powerlifting Meet!!! Stefani Norton and Cassandra Arroyo took 1st in their weight classes. Norton set a new Regional Record with a total of 955lbs. Arroyo also set a Regional Record with a squat of 350lbs. Also Medaling were Brooke Daniels with a 3rd place finish as well as Myah Soza and Mattie Willingham with 5th place finishes. Norton and Arroyoa are now headed to the Girls State Powerlifting Meet!!! Community Independent School District

post_text: Way to go Braves!!! 🏆
shared_text:
Community FFA
February 22 at 12:05 PM ·

It’s been a few years since we have had an Ag Mech project at a major show. I am so proud of the work these kids put into this cooker. They learned how to draw plans, break down of cost, decide what and how much material was needed, then they used the skills they learned all year to build it. They had to measure, cut, weld, grind and paint. They had to create a book from start to finish. This was a collaborative effort.

All this hard work earned them a BLUE ribbon at the San Antonio Ag Mech Show. There were 180 in that class. They will go on to compete for division. No matter what that outcome is, our kids and Mr. Bedell did a fabulous job!!

I would also like to thank the Community FFA Alumni Association for having faith in our kids and Mr. Bedell to purchase material for this cooker. Hopefully next year they can build a trailer to show their talents on a larger scale.

Lots of job opportunities for these kids in their future!!

post_text: Be on the lookout for shiny new buses on the Brave Nation roads. Last summer, the Community ISD Transportation Department applied for a grant made available by the Texas Commission on Environment Quality as part of The Texas Volkswagen Environmental Mitigation Program. The district received $442,800 in grant money to purchase six new buses! These new buses all have air conditioning, active collision mitigation and seatbelts. We are SUPER excited to be replacing the six oldest buses in our fleet with four new 77 passenger buses and two 88 passenger buses for our fastest growing routes.

Last week the Edge Middle School counselors and our CISD Child Nutrition team got together to help our EMS Braves celebrate National Make a Friend Day (Tuesday, February 11) and No One Eats Alone Day (Friday, February 14)

This is the 2nd year the campus has celebrated No One Eats Alone Week. This year, Edge has approximately 100 students who are new to our district, so during the week known for love and friendship our EMS Student Council handed out coupons during lunch to these new Braves and invited them to share a GIANT cookie or chocolate covered strawberries with new friends! #NoOneEatsAlone #BravesAreGenerous #MakeAFriend

Last week, McClendon Elementary received a visit from the co-creator of the Gómez and Gómez Dual Language Enrichment Model, Dr. Richard Gomez. During his visit, Dr. Gomez evaluated the overall campus-wide implementation, individual dual language classroom instruction, as well as the overall learning environment at MES.

Four of our teachers received EXEMPLARY status and received a star on their official Gomez and Gomez lanyard! Congratulations to Mrs. Zingg for receiving her second consecutive exemplary star, along with Mr. Padilla, Mrs. Sepulvado, and Mr. Camacho! Teachers must meet specific elements in classroom environment, instructional processes, and student learning to reach exemplary.

We are SO proud of all our BRAVE dual language teachers and our passionate leadership team at MES!

Do you need to Brag on a Brave? Visit our website communityisd.org/Brag for a simple way to compliment a Community ISD employee, student or volunteer you observe demonstrating the Traits of a Brave: being generous, humble, passionate and wise.

The Traits of a Brave define the positive character, choices and behavior we expect from our Braves at every level. This is your opportunity to help us celebrate and acknowledge members of the Brave Nation who exemplify these traits! Once a month Brag on a Brave certificates will be delivered to those who have been nominated and a list of recipients will be published on the CISD website.

shared_text:
US National Weather Service Fort Worth Texas
January 10 at 10:34 AM ·

Today is a day to pay attention to the weather! All modes of severe weather are possible beginning as early as mid afternoon and into the evening hours.

There are several ways to receive weather warnings. Not every method is perfect, which is why we recommend having multiple ways to receive warnings!

Please follow/monitor our Twitter feed to monitor rapid weather updates this afternoon/evening. You don't need a Twitter account to see our tweets! https://twitter.com/NWSFortWorth

post_text:
2020 is a BIG year for Community ISD as we will open our brand new CHS campus in August! We will also be moving the Edge Middle School campus to their newly renovated home across the street in January 2021. So, we are already busy planning for the exciting upcoming school year!

As with any year, we know that the school calendar impacts our families and community and we want to provide an opportunity for you to give us your feedback on the proposed 2020-21 CISD calendar.

Please take a moment to complete the brief survey before January 31, 2020. All feedback will be considered before a final version of the 2020-21 school calendar is presented to the board for approval in February.

post_text:
Alumni Spotlight: CHS graduate (Class of 2017) and UNT soccer star Logan Bruffett was recently named to the Google Cloud Academic All-America soccer team. Bruffett was also a first-team member of the Conference USA All-Academic team. Logan was Valedictorian of her class at Community High School and has continued her impressive academic accomplishments at the University of North Texas. She holds a 4.00 GPA as an integrative studies major while studying psychology, biology and health. In 2019, Logan earned the UNT Golden Eagle Award, which is the highest student-leadership award at UNT. The #BraveNation is SO proud of you and we can't wait to watch you continue to soar!! 💛🦅⚽️

#OnceABraveAlwaysaBrave

post_text: Meet CISD Officer Maria Peralta, a Brave since August 2018. A native of Dallas, she began her career & training at Eastfield College. Prior to joining CISDPD, she served several years as a reserve Officer for the City of Lavon. Officer Peralta has a passion for creating positive & caring interactions with students and hopes to make an impact on their lives beyond high school. Officer Peralta holds a Basic Peace Officer License and earned her associate’s degree from Eastfield College. Thank you for keeping our Braves and #CommUNITY safe!

post_text:
This holiday season, the best gift you can give your child is a great education. And the best place to get that
education is in school. Every day. On time.

Every year we see our absences spike in the weeks before and after holiday breaks. We know family time is important and it’s tempting to extend your vacation by a few days on either side of the holiday. We are sharing this reminder of the dates for our Thanksgiving and Christmas breaks this year and asking for your help as you plan your holiday travel. We need our Braves to be back in our classrooms when break is over and we need them in #SchoolEveryday.

post_text: Let's meet CISD Police Officer Chuck Sibley. He began his 2nd career as a police officer for the City of Sachse in 2009, after retiring from the Navy where he served as a Military Police Officer for 21 years. He served as an investigator for the Collin County Sheriff’s Office until joining the CISD PD in 2018. Officer Sibley is an Advanced Peace Officer and Mental Health Peace Officer. He also has deep ties to #CommUNITY as a longtime resident and father of CISD alumni. Thanks for all you do to keep our Braves safe!

post_text:
Let's get to know our CISD Police Chief Scotty Morrison. He has been a Brave since the CISD Police Department was established in July 2017. He is a Master Peace Officer, Mental Health Peace Officer, SRO Instructor, and Firearms Instructor. Chief Morrison has a Master’s Degree in Criminal Justice Leadership and Management from Sam Houston State University. He is also a graduate of the Bill Blackwood Law Enforcement Management Institute of Texas’ Leadership Command College. Chief Morrison grew up in McKinney, Texas. When he is not busy keeping our Braves safe, he enjoys camping, kayaking and mountain biking.

Thank you for all you do to keep our Community ISD students, staff and guests safe!

post_text:
#SafeBraves Update 3:22 PM the lock-out has been lifted as there is no longer police activity in the area. EMS & CHS will dismiss as usual.

#SafeBraves (October 16, 2019 at 3:05 PM)

Due to police activity in the area and out of an abundance of caution, the three campuses in Nevada (McClendon, Edge and CHS) are on a "lock-out" meaning all exterior doors are locked, students must remain in the building and visitors are not allowed on campus.

McClendon is dismissing as usual with the CISD Police Department on site for extra security. Parents needing to pick up students early from EMS and CHS will be allowed into the office. We do not expect for EMS or CHS dismissal to be impacted, however if the situation changes we will update this post.
text:
#SafeBraves Update 3:22 PM the lock-out has been lifted as there is no longer police activity in the area. EMS & CHS will dismiss as usual.

#SafeBraves (October 16, 2019 at 3:05 PM)

Due to police activity in the area and out of an abundance of caution, the three campuses in Nevada (McClendon, Edge and CHS) are on a "lock-out" meaning all exterior doors are locked, students must remain in the building and visitors are not allowed on campus.

McClendon is dismissing as usual with the CISD Police Department on site for extra security. Parents needing to pick up students early from EMS and CHS will be allowed into the office. We do not expect for EMS or CHS dismissal to be impacted, however if the situation changes we will update this post.

McClendon Elementary
October 14, 2019 at 10:00 PM ·

Dear McClendon Braves, we need to share some sad news and ask for your help. The home of one of our very own MES families burned this weekend. Thankfully, no one was injured but the family is in need of our support. We are asking for donations of gift cards only to be dropped off at the CISD administration office on Tuesday 10/15 or Wednesday & Thursday at our campus office. The gift cards can be in any amount and to any place that will help the family replace clothing/household items, purchase food/groceries, etc. We will deliver the gift cards to the family on Friday 10/18. (Important note: we will not be accepting any donations of items or clothing so as to not burden the family with unneeded items)

post_text: Teachers and staff in Community ISD have until 4PM on October 4, 2019, to apply for a grant from the Community ISD Education Foundation. Last year, the Foundation handed out over $10,000 in grants to teachers in CISD. One of the grants received by CHS Science teacher Tammy McDaniel resulted in this amazing learning experience for our Braves! A weather balloon launched by her students traveled 40,000 feet into the atmosphere before falling back to earth and providing the class with amazing data and information to study. We can't wait to see what amazing learning experiences our passionate teachers will apply for this year! Thanks to the CISD Education Foundation for supporting our Braves.

post_text: Meet the 4th member of our CISD Police Department, Officer Chris Holland. He joined the CISDPD in August of 2019. Officer Holland brings over 27 years of experience as a police officer, most recently as a member of the Sachse Police Department. A native of Rockwall, Officer Holland is married to his high school sweetheart and they have three grown children. Officer Holland will call McClendon Elementary home this school year. He is excited to be serving the Brave Nation & we are thankful he is here to keep our Braves safe! #SafeBraves #CISDPD #WeAreBraves

post_text:
Are you looking for a part time job but don’t want to miss spending time with your school aged child?

We just might have the answer....Community ISD is looking for a new team member for our Child Nutrition Team!

Flexible work days (4-8 hours/day)

Off on school holidays, weekends and summer.

Great working environment (uniforms provided and free breakfast/lunch)

Great Benefits, including health, dental, vision and life insurance.

Competitive wages ranging from $10.58/hour (Cafeteria Specialist) to $11.55/hour (Assistant Manager)

Cafeteria team members must:
Be neat, clean and organized and have a “team player” attitude.

Be able to read and record various information including temperatures.

Be courteous and friendly to students, educators and co-workers.

Be able to follow safety and sanitation procedures.

If you would like the opportunity to work with fun and friendly individuals who care about our CISD students and teachers while you continue to enjoy your child’s schedule...

PLEASE CONTACT:
Child Nutrition Office @ 972-843-6081
